# I got rate limited... by basketball-reference.com
# Thank god for Express VPN (Its an advertisement!!)
# Anyway even with Express, I couldn't collect all the data
# at once so I split it into 4 seperate sets holding data.
# This data set represents all per game data for every player
# for every year from 1951 - 2022 (for some reason Express)
# couldn't get me back 1950 even though I used it to test the code

nba_stats = []
# 1951 - 1970
for i in range(20):
    val = 1950+i+1
    data_url = (f'https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_'+str(val)+'_per_game.html')

    play_res = requests.get(data_url)
    res_soup = BeautifulSoup(play_res.content, 'lxml')
    nba_per_game = res_soup.find(name = 'table', attrs = {'id' : 'per_game_stats'})
    for row in nba_per_game.find_all('tr',{'class': 'full_table'}):

        # All publically available data until 1975. We'll use this for everything!
        player = {}
        player['Name'] = row.find('a').text.strip()
        player['Num Games'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'g'}).text
        player['Field Goals PG'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'fg_per_g'}).text
        player['Field Goal %'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'fg_pct'}).text
        player['Field Goal %'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'fg_pct'}).text
        player['Two Point PG'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'fg2_per_g'}).text
        player['Two Point %'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'fg2_pct'}).text
        player['Free Throws'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'ft_per_g'}).text
        player['Free Throw %'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'ft_pct'}).text
        player['Assists PG'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'ast_per_g'}).text
        player['Personal Fouls'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'pf_per_g'}).text
        player['Points PG'] = row.find('td', {'data-stat' : 'pts_per_g'}).text
        nba_stats.append(player)

pd.DataFrame(nba_stats)

#NBA Data from 1950 - 2002
#Note, due to the three year for the NBA, by going up to the 2001-2002 season,
#there will be 3 legends that would not have been elegible for being HOFed
#included in the training set. Tyson Chandler (2001 - 2020), Jamal 
#Crawford (2000 - 2020), and Vince Carter (1998 - 2020). Due to their
#retirement in 2020, they have not yet reached the 3 year mark required to
#join the HOF yet they played before 2002. For this reason, they will
#be excluded from the training set

NBA_STATS = NBA_STATS.drop(columns='Num Games')

NBA_STATS = NBA_STATS[NBA_STATS['Name'] != 'Tyson Chandler']
NBA_STATS = NBA_STATS[NBA_STATS['Name'] != 'Jamal Crawford']
NBA_STATS = NBA_STATS[NBA_STATS['Name'] != 'Vince Carter']

Next we want to use groupby to combine all the data for each person as a list. From the list, we can then create the new table. However, note we also want to remove all shared names between NBA_STATS, our training sample, and nbaSatatsPd4, the set we will eventually try to predict. There will of course be overlap for any players who have played both before and after 2002

And now, after a long and arduous process, the data is finally clean and easy to work with! With that, we can finally split our test data into a train and test set with a nice 80/20 split! After that, we will add two times our HOFall set into the train data to oversample because, as shown above, there are only a total of 136 HOF'd NBA players but a rather impressive 2742 players distinct players playing the game before the 2001-2002 season meaning less that without oversampling, an algorithm that guesses not HOF 100% of the time would have over 95% accuracy. Hopefully adding 272 HOF-positive samples directly into the training set will discourage a pointless algorithm of that form!

For this experiment, we will be testing out Four different algorithms. KNN, Decision Tree, Neural Network, and Clustering! Let us begin by seeing what variables may matter

So why does it almost always cap at 93%, a number that is actually worse then the accuracy that should have been recieved from only guessing not HOF? Well one major issue was how, at least in this case, the oversampling took place. Although it made sense to increase the number of HOFers, the HOFers that are shown are all stacked but they still cover the same amount of area as if they weren't stacked. Overall, it simiply didn't make sense to use a K neighbors classifier on this dataset

After the failiure that occurred from KNN, I decided to try to work with decision trees! Decision trees are generally stronger with classification variables so I was interested in seeing how well one would preform on my data set!

To my dissapointment, the Gaussian Matrix, which seemed like it would have been a perfect fit for this problem, failed to return positive results. In the end the only classifier that had a higher test accuracy than just always returning Not HOF was the neural network and even then just barely. Although it is clear what some massive errors are in this project (lack of large enough dataset and too few explored features), there are also multiple ways in which this project can be expanded further. Firstly, one stat that I had not examined that could most definitely be used is the number of games played per player per season. Using that, we could find the average points per game or shots per game between two years rather than treating the two years the player played as entirely distinct. This would also allow for me to more fairly analyze players who only played for one year. Secondly, I had some "strings" apparently in my player dataset but I never actually figured out where they came from or what they represent. Overall, I believe I could have expanded on data exploration and better implemented algorithms given more time but I am happy with what I did end up finding.
